00:27:09,498 --> 00:27:11,359
So green means better and red means worse.

553
00:27:12,200 --> 00:27:13,881
And then the icons represent the things themselves.

554
00:27:14,681 --> 00:27:15,562
And it's just super great.

555
00:27:15,582 --> 00:27:16,602
They could have garbage that up

556
00:27:16,642 --> 00:27:18,664
with a ton of like bars and texts

557
00:27:18,704 --> 00:27:19,824
and a whole bunch of things,

558
00:27:19,864 --> 00:27:21,605
but they found a really, really simple way to do it.

559
00:27:23,474 --> 00:27:29,416
Orny, hide, merge, evacuate, you'll recall, kill.

560
00:27:29,456 --> 00:27:30,777
Last, I think, Dotson Co. example,

561
00:27:30,817 --> 00:27:32,637
just because I know a lot about it.

562
00:27:33,038 --> 00:27:36,059
This was the original character select screen.

563
00:27:37,179 --> 00:27:39,080
In Dotson Co., you have a little companion

564
00:27:39,120 --> 00:27:41,061
who goes with you into the game and helps you out each level.

565
00:27:41,841 --> 00:27:44,322
The original concept was that you would have

566
00:27:44,582 --> 00:27:47,463
a rookie and an expert companion available each level.

567
00:27:48,063 --> 00:27:50,784
The rookie was free, the expert cost hard currency,

568
00:27:50,824 --> 00:27:51,805
but was more powerful.

569
00:27:54,586 --> 00:28:02,929
And we put a ton of work into finding the right way to make this choice clean.

570
00:28:05,150 --> 00:28:11,052
And we stuck button upon button upon button and tried swiping paradigm upon swiping paradigm.

571
00:28:12,332 --> 00:28:17,314
Just got into a situation where we could, you know, you were, you were.

572
00:28:18,235 --> 00:28:19,456
chasing your tail, you would fix this problem

573
00:28:19,476 --> 00:28:20,956
and then cause a new problem and run and run and run.

574
00:28:20,976 --> 00:28:21,296
You would go.

575
00:28:21,957 --> 00:28:24,477
And where we ended up was here.

576
00:28:28,499 --> 00:28:31,239
So it's the same mono button solution.

577
00:28:32,820 --> 00:28:36,441
So again, rather than having to navigate button

578
00:28:36,501 --> 00:28:38,762
plus illustrative element plus informational element,

579
00:28:39,282 --> 00:28:40,162
everything's bundled together.

580
00:28:41,311 --> 00:28:42,472
But the other thing you'll notice

581
00:28:42,512 --> 00:28:43,613
is we basically killed the feature.

582
00:28:43,853 --> 00:28:46,435
This is a different take on the same feature.

583
00:28:46,495 --> 00:28:48,856
So there's still an option to make a hard currency

584
00:28:48,876 --> 00:28:51,078
purchase to up your chances of beating the level.

585
00:28:51,518 --> 00:28:53,059
But we lost the idea that there would

586
00:28:53,079 --> 00:28:55,181
be two separate characters that you were choosing between,

587
00:28:55,581 --> 00:28:58,203
because it was just too much of an information

588
00:28:58,243 --> 00:29:00,024
burden at a moment in the game where

589
00:29:00,044 --> 00:29:03,707
you want things to be smooth and fast and about anticipation.

590
00:29:05,208 --> 00:29:08,370
So we killed the, well, we didn't kill the penguin,

591
00:29:08,971 --> 00:29:09,931
but sort of.

592
00:29:10,492 --> 00:29:10,932
Sorry, Anita.

593
00:29:11,764 --> 00:29:12,424
She's wearing a scarf.

594
00:29:13,945 --> 00:29:15,446
OK, I'm definitely over time, so these

595
00:29:15,486 --> 00:29:16,526
are going to go crazy fast.

596
00:29:17,547 --> 00:29:19,688
Orny wouldn't be Orny without some kind of secret weapon.

597
00:29:19,728 --> 00:29:20,708
This is our secret weapon.

598
00:29:21,149 --> 00:29:22,449
I can't recommend this strongly enough.

599
00:29:24,270 --> 00:29:28,012
Everything we make is 100% colorblind playable.

600
00:29:30,373 --> 00:29:32,274
And it's an enormous amount of work.

601
00:29:32,994 --> 00:29:34,535
And it's prodigiously worthwhile.

602
00:29:36,036 --> 00:29:39,998
So this is a pretty complex Docks and Coast screen.

603
00:29:40,853 --> 00:29:41,874
We've got a bunch of stuff going on.

604
00:29:41,914 --> 00:29:44,815
We've got dots that explode into squares.

605
00:29:44,855 --> 00:29:46,616
We've got dots that auto-connect to other dots.

606
00:29:46,656 --> 00:29:48,898
We've got dots that auto-connect to other dots that are inside.

607
00:29:49,458 --> 00:29:50,858
Dots that only open when you match next to them.

608
00:29:50,879 --> 00:29:51,999
And there's balloons that are going up

609
00:29:52,019 --> 00:29:52,839
to the top of the screen.

610
00:29:53,380 --> 00:29:54,820
There's panels that change the color

611
00:29:54,840 --> 00:29:55,861
of dots that fall into them.

612
00:29:58,242 --> 00:30:02,384
It's all moderately overwhelming from a design perspective

613
00:30:03,245 --> 00:30:04,165
if you're just playing.

614
00:30:04,205 --> 00:30:07,547
But if you turn colorblind on, now all of that

615
00:30:07,587 --> 00:30:10,248
has to function successfully.

616
00:30:12,284 --> 00:30:14,909
with the shape system that we have on top of that.

617
00:30:14,949 --> 00:30:16,552
And every single mechanic that we put in the game,

618
00:30:16,692 --> 00:30:19,498
even if it seems like we don't know how to do it,

619
00:30:19,918 --> 00:30:21,541
we won't put in unless we can make colorblind work.

620
00:30:23,340 --> 00:30:25,042
And we do that because it's nice.

621
00:30:25,462 --> 00:30:27,544
You wouldn't believe how many letters we get from people.

622
00:30:27,564 --> 00:30:28,865
You wouldn't believe how many people

623
00:30:28,925 --> 00:30:30,085
don't think they're colorblind,

624
00:30:30,145 --> 00:30:31,486
but still find it incredibly useful

625
00:30:31,567 --> 00:30:33,088
to have that kind of facility within a game.

626
00:30:33,408 --> 00:30:34,289
Super, super worthwhile.

627
00:30:34,869 --> 00:30:37,311
It's an incredibly good discipline for us as designers.

628
00:30:40,533 --> 00:30:44,156
It just forces you to be incredibly restrained

629
00:30:44,196 --> 00:30:46,518
and precise in how you work.

630
00:30:47,078 --> 00:30:47,198
And...

631
00:30:49,907 --> 00:30:53,008
Because you figured out all of your colorblind design

632
00:30:53,028 --> 00:30:55,549
at a formal level, it gives you the freedom

633
00:30:55,569 --> 00:30:57,270
to do whatever the hell you want with color anywhere else.

634
00:30:57,390 --> 00:31:00,951
And that maybe is the thing that is the most vital tool

635
00:31:00,991 --> 00:31:02,851
in our toolbox for doing good minimal design,

636
00:31:03,251 --> 00:31:07,352
which is that we invest a wildly high proportion

637
00:31:07,372 --> 00:31:08,913
of our energy into color.

638
00:31:09,933 --> 00:31:12,594
So we redo the palette of the game.

639
00:31:14,144 --> 00:31:17,026
Every, this is two dots so far,

640
00:31:17,206 --> 00:31:18,227
Dots & Co also does this.

641
00:31:20,028 --> 00:31:23,070
It's a huge amount of work to settle on those palettes

642
00:31:23,090 --> 00:31:24,811
and then make sure everything works against everything else.

643
00:31:25,191 --> 00:31:27,633
It's unbelievably worthwhile because it is a way

644
00:31:27,673 --> 00:31:30,775
of giving the game a sense of richness and luxury

645
00:31:31,696 --> 00:31:34,658
without adding detail or texture or complex illustration.

646
00:31:36,619 --> 00:31:40,541
And so that kind of double whammy of using colorblind

647
00:31:40,581 --> 00:31:41,922
as an opportunity to make sure that our designs

648
00:31:41,962 --> 00:31:43,263
are really, really, really restrained.

649
00:31:43,777 --> 00:31:47,240
and then being able to do things with color was fantastic.

650
00:31:48,861 --> 00:31:51,983
I got one thing that's cooler than rainbow ink.

651
00:31:55,286 --> 00:31:58,268
Invisible ink.

652
00:31:59,569 --> 00:32:01,170
These are the design elements that we use

653
00:32:02,772 --> 00:32:04,233
to make our minimal design work

654
00:32:04,253 --> 00:32:05,233
that don't show up on screen.

655
00:32:06,735 --> 00:32:07,735
This is the biggest one.

656
00:32:09,377 --> 00:32:09,917
Music and sound.

657
00:32:11,630 --> 00:32:13,091
If you're trying to do minimal design

658
00:32:13,151 --> 00:32:15,731
and you're not including these as a cornerstone

659
00:32:15,791 --> 00:32:16,832
of how your design is gonna work,

660
00:32:16,872 --> 00:32:19,452
you're making life way harder for yourself

661
00:32:19,472 --> 00:32:20,132
than it needs to be.

662
00:32:21,413 --> 00:32:25,474
We're unbelievably reliant on how smart our sound team are

663
00:32:26,534 --> 00:32:28,875
for supporting the work that we try and do

664
00:32:28,915 --> 00:32:31,035
in terms of the aesthetic that we're trying to hit.

665
00:32:31,515 --> 00:32:35,336
And then that also goes for things like vibration.

666
00:32:35,616 --> 00:32:36,117
Did that buzz?

667
00:32:39,205 --> 00:32:44,960
Yeah, one of the best bits of visual design we have in the game is that when you make a square, it buzzes.

668
00:32:46,077 --> 00:32:47,757
And because it buzzes, we don't have to do anything else.

669
00:32:48,058 --> 00:32:48,978
We actually do do some other things,

670
00:32:49,018 --> 00:32:50,559
but we have to do so much less

671
00:32:50,639 --> 00:32:51,839
because we have that vibration in there.

672
00:32:52,480 --> 00:32:55,481
So when you're hitting a ceiling visually,

673
00:32:55,501 --> 00:32:57,102
you're like, there's more I need to communicate,

674
00:32:57,142 --> 00:32:58,303
but my screen's getting too busy,

675
00:32:58,343 --> 00:33:00,924
this thing's starting to feel noisy and not minimal enough,

676
00:33:01,284 --> 00:33:03,125
remember that you have other tools at your disposal

677
00:33:03,145 --> 00:33:03,825
that aren't visual.

678
00:33:04,386 --> 00:33:05,926
Because I think that's the thing

679
00:33:05,946 --> 00:33:07,147
that I've been most conscious of

680
00:33:07,307 --> 00:33:09,308
coming to work at this company.

681
00:33:10,649 --> 00:33:11,729
We're 50 people now.

682
00:33:11,749 --> 00:33:11,809
And...

683
00:33:15,472 --> 00:33:18,874
If everyone doesn't buy into the virtue

684
00:33:18,894 --> 00:33:21,996
of a minimal aesthetic, you're gonna have

685
00:33:22,036 --> 00:33:23,436
a really hard time holding onto it,

686
00:33:23,557 --> 00:33:25,198
especially in a commercial setting.

687
00:33:26,779 --> 00:33:27,979
Minimalist is fragile.

688
00:33:28,019 --> 00:33:29,600
You can ruin it real quick just by sticking

689
00:33:29,640 --> 00:33:32,062
an extra button in there, or a new texture,

690
00:33:32,122 --> 00:33:34,283
or a dumb keynote animation transition

691
00:33:34,323 --> 00:33:34,863
that I should.

692
00:33:36,360 --> 00:33:37,481
not use but I can't resist.

693
00:33:38,121 --> 00:33:41,604
You need everybody to be invested in keeping things clear

694
00:33:41,644 --> 00:33:42,545
and keeping things clean,

695
00:33:42,945 --> 00:33:44,406
in figuring out how their discipline,

696
00:33:44,426 --> 00:33:46,788
whether they're game designers or product managers

697
00:33:46,808 --> 00:33:49,870
or musicians or whatever else they do,

698
00:33:50,971 --> 00:33:55,154
can hold the line and let the work stay clean and beautiful

699
00:33:55,995 --> 00:33:56,575
as you want it to be.

